==English==

===Etymology===
{{L.}} ''[[reticens]]'', present participle of ''[[reticere]]'' to keep silence; [[re-]] + [[tacere]] to be silent.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈrɛtɪsənt/}}
*{{audio|en-us-reticent.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Keeping one's [[thought]]s and [[opinion]]s to [[oneself]]; [[reserved]] or [[restrained]].

====Quotations====
*'''1891''' — [[w:Thomas Hardy|Thomas Hardy]] ,''[[s:Tess of the d'Urbervilles|Tess of the d'Urbervilles]]'', ch LIV
*:She had told him she was not now at Marlott, but had been curiously reticent as to her actual address, and the only course was to go to Marlott and inquire for it.

====Synonyms====
* [[reserved]], [[restrained]], [[tight-lipped]]

